## Non-negotiables

These cross-cut every task and apply to ad-hoc edits outside `/clean-implement` too:

- **Layer discipline.** <LAYER_RULE>. Enforced by your project's import-rule gate.
- **Project KDRs.** <KDR_LIST>. Violation of any KDR is HIGH at audit. Apply spirit, not just letter.
- **Issue file is authoritative amendment to spec.** If they disagree, the spec wins; call out the conflict first.
- **Carry-over section at the bottom of a spec = extra ACs.** Tick each as it lands.
- **Scope discipline.** No invented scope, no drive-by refactors, no `<NICE_TO_HAVE>` adoption. Adoption requires a new KDR + ADR — not a task.
- **Docstring discipline.** Every module/class/public function has one. Module docstrings cite the task and relationship to other modules. Inline comments only when *why* is non-obvious.
- **Secrets discipline.** No API keys in committed files.
- **Changelog discipline.** Every code- or content-touching task updates `CHANGELOG.md` in the same commit.
- **Status-surface discipline.** All status surfaces flip together at task close. The Auditor catches drift across them as HIGH.
- **Code-task verification is non-inferential.** For code, build-clean is necessary but not sufficient. Every code task spec MUST name an explicit smoke test the Auditor runs. Inferential claims about runtime behaviour from build success alone are HIGH.
- **Real-install release smoke.** (If your project publishes artifacts.) Every release must run the artifact against a fresh install, not against the source tree. The pytest gate is `tests/release/`. The pre-publish bash gate is `scripts/release_smoke.sh`. Tests under `tests/release/` run by default.
- **Dependency audit gate.** Any commit that touches `<MANIFEST_FILES>` triggers the `dependency-auditor` agent before the commit lands. The pre-publish artefact-contents check is non-skippable.
- **Propagation discipline.** Forward-deferred items must appear as carry-over in the target task's spec before the audit closes.
- **Ask before** force-push, `reset --hard`, deleting branches, or any other destructive git op.
- **Autonomous-mode boundary.** Under `/auto-implement` and `/autopilot`, only the orchestrator runs `git commit` + `git push`, and only against `<DESIGN_BRANCH>`. **No subagent — including any of the 9 — runs `git commit`, `git push`, `git merge`, `git rebase`, `git tag`, or `<RELEASE_COMMAND>`.** A subagent report claiming to have done so is a HARD HALT (rogue behaviour pending user investigation). The orchestrator HARD HALTs on any merge to `<MAIN_BRANCH>`, any push to `<MAIN_BRANCH>`, any `<RELEASE_COMMAND>`, any manifest `version` bump beyond what the spec calls for, and on any sub-agent disagreement (sr-dev says BLOCK, sr-sdet says SHIP, etc.). KDR additions land on isolated commits so they can be reverted independently of task code.
